1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,487
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa.

2
00:00:09,368 --> 00:00:17,583
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa.

3
00:00:18,204 --> 00:00:33,524
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:33,564 --> 00:00:39,612
So we continue with our exploration of the Buddha's teaching about lay life.

5
00:00:39,633 --> 00:00:44,820
I thought I would do this one which is rather quaint to our modern ears.

6
00:00:45,593 --> 00:00:48,796
But it tells us a little bit about that society.

7
00:00:49,677 --> 00:00:53,101
And I don't think it's that too distant from us.

8
00:00:54,423 --> 00:01:02,893
You might have said these things to a woman in the, well, right up until the 1960s, really.

9
00:01:03,795 --> 00:01:09,542
Anyway, this is, Bikobodi's called it the woman of the home.

10
00:01:11,284 --> 00:01:11,905
So,

11
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:19,587
On one occasion, the Blessed One was dwelling at Sarvati in the Eastern Park in the mansion of Migara's mother.

12
00:01:20,650 --> 00:01:26,977
Then Visakha, Migara's mother, approached the Blessed One, paid homage to him and sat to one side.

13
00:01:27,658 --> 00:01:32,524
Visakha was one of his main disciples, very rich.

14
00:01:33,385 --> 00:01:37,930
And as you can see, it was in her park, so pretty well off.

15
00:01:38,409 --> 00:01:42,415
And the Blessed One then said to her, Visakha,

16
00:01:43,322 --> 00:01:50,393
When a woman possesses four qualities, she's heading for victory in the present world and is successful in this world.

17
00:01:51,634 --> 00:01:52,094
What for?

18
00:01:52,695 --> 00:02:02,668
Here, Visakha, a woman is capable at her work, she manages her domestic help, she behaves in a way that is agreeable to her husband, and she safeguards his earnings.

19
00:02:06,353 --> 00:02:12,823
So these days you can put partner where it's a woman, but I'm keeping it to woman because it's...

20
00:02:13,612 --> 00:02:15,155
It gives us a flavour of his time.

21
00:02:16,336 --> 00:02:18,198
And how is a woman capable at her work?

22
00:02:18,298 --> 00:02:25,144
Here, Visakha, she is skilful and diligent in regard to her husband's household chores, whether with wool or cotton.

23
00:02:27,205 --> 00:02:31,371
She investigates the appropriate means and is able to act and arrange everything properly.

24
00:02:31,770 --> 00:02:36,074
And in this way, a woman is capable at her work.

25
00:02:36,094 --> 00:02:38,937
So this tells you a little bit about what a woman at home might do.

26
00:02:40,359 --> 00:02:42,961
Knitting, very much like

27
00:02:43,651 --> 00:02:50,658
You would expect somebody in, say, well, right up until, say, the 60s.

28
00:02:51,560 --> 00:02:56,425
And how is a woman one who manages the domestic help?

29
00:02:56,444 --> 00:02:59,427
So this is only for those rare rich people.

30
00:02:59,868 --> 00:03:05,375
Hear Visakha in regard to her husband's domestic helpers, slaves, servants, and workers.

31
00:03:05,975 --> 00:03:09,719
She knows by direct inspection what they have done and failed to do.

32
00:03:10,219 --> 00:03:13,623
She knows when they are sick and healthy, and she distributes to each

33
00:03:13,856 --> 00:03:15,359
the appropriate share of food.

34
00:03:15,780 --> 00:03:19,724
And in this way, a woman manages domestic help.

35
00:03:19,745 --> 00:03:25,693
Now this would take you to upstairs downstairs, wouldn't it?

36
00:03:25,712 --> 00:03:26,693
Don't know about the slaves.

37
00:03:27,275 --> 00:03:27,975
That goes back a bit.

38
00:03:29,957 --> 00:03:33,122
And how does a woman behave in a way that is agreeable to her husband?

39
00:03:33,562 --> 00:03:40,733
Here, Visakha, a woman would not commit any misdeed that her husband would consider disagreeable, even at the cost of her life.

40
00:03:41,734 --> 00:03:42,615
Now those are the days.

41
00:03:44,317 --> 00:03:49,692
In this way, a woman behaves in a way that is agreeable to her husband.

42
00:03:54,786 --> 00:03:59,759
We have to remember that in the book of Manu, which is a sort of Brahminical text,

43
00:04:00,819 --> 00:04:25,899
a woman is seen to be as a chattel of the husband and a woman is not capable of liberating herself because she can't get moksha she has to be reborn as a man so you can see how when the Buddha came along and liberated women from that oppression

44
00:04:26,470 --> 00:04:29,995
saying that they could be fully liberated in this very lifetime.

45
00:04:30,014 --> 00:04:30,956
It was like men.

46
00:04:31,898 --> 00:04:33,661
It was revolutionary, really.

47
00:04:39,810 --> 00:04:42,394
And how does a woman safeguard her husband's earnings?

48
00:04:42,673 --> 00:04:55,093
Here, Visakha, whatever a husband brings home, whether money or grain, silver or gold, she succeeds in protecting it and guarding it, and she's not a spendthrift, thief, wastrel, or squanderer of his wealth.

49
00:04:55,646 --> 00:04:59,932
And in this way, a woman safeguards her husband's earnings.

50
00:05:01,475 --> 00:05:06,283
I'm just thinking of this Indian man who came to the Bihara once, years ago.

51
00:05:09,007 --> 00:05:15,776
He was in a sort of state of, I think he was overcoming shock.

52
00:05:15,797 --> 00:05:22,346
What had happened was he had done the thing of handing over his wages to his wife.

53
00:05:23,557 --> 00:05:25,620
And she had taken care of all the expenses.

54
00:05:26,521 --> 00:05:32,468
And unknowing to him, she'd been sending this huge amount of money home to her side of the family.

55
00:05:34,389 --> 00:05:36,432
And he'd found this out a wee bit late in life.

56
00:05:36,452 --> 00:05:37,394
He was about to retire.

57
00:05:38,495 --> 00:05:46,444
So they were obviously spent through a thief, you see, wasteful, and a squanderer of his wealth.

58
00:05:49,326 --> 00:05:56,497
When, Visakha, a woman possesses these four qualities, she's heading for victory in the present world and is successful in this world.

59
00:05:57,016 --> 00:06:03,706
And when she possesses four other qualities, she's heading for victory in the other world and is successful in regard to the other world.

60
00:06:03,745 --> 00:06:04,406
And what for?

61
00:06:05,829 --> 00:06:10,935
So here, Visakha, a woman is accomplished in faith, moral discipline, generosity, and wisdom.

62
00:06:11,536 --> 00:06:13,418
And how is a woman accomplished in faith?

63
00:06:14,019 --> 00:06:15,702
Here, Visakha, a woman has faith.

64
00:06:16,142 --> 00:06:19,047
She places faith in the enlightenment of the Tathagata.

65
00:06:19,701 --> 00:06:24,916
So notice that, not in the Tathāgata, in the enlightenment of the Tathāgata, in the enlightenment of the Buddha.

66
00:06:27,846 --> 00:06:30,112
And how is a woman accomplished in moral discipline?

67
00:06:30,273 --> 00:06:32,158
So your basic moral law.

68
00:06:32,475 --> 00:06:42,555
abstains from destruction of life, from stealing, from sexual misconduct, from false speech, and from wines, liquors, intoxicants, the basis for negligence.

69
00:06:42,574 --> 00:06:49,007
So that's the main reason for not taking intoxicants is the basis for negligence.

70
00:06:49,026 --> 00:06:51,571
You do things under the influence that you wouldn't normally do.

71
00:06:53,615 --> 00:06:56,339
In this way a woman is accomplished in moral discipline.

72
00:06:57,163 --> 00:06:59,346
And how is a woman accomplished in generosity?

73
00:06:59,468 --> 00:07:13,127
Here, Visakha, a woman dwells at home with a mind devoid of the stain of stinginess, freely generous, open-handed, delighting in relinquishment, one devoted to charity, delighting in giving and sharing.

74
00:07:13,468 --> 00:07:15,793
And in this way a woman is accomplished in generosity.

75
00:07:17,033 --> 00:07:21,500
Generosity comes up very much in the Buddhist teaching.

76
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:24,605
Whenever he gives a talk to lay people, he always starts with generosity.

77
00:07:25,226 --> 00:07:50,391
and here it's beautifully put why we should be generous devoid of the stain of stinginess freely generous open-handed so these are all just adjectives for you know generosity but delighting in relinquishment delighting in relinquish that's tough isn't it delighting in giving something away

78
00:07:51,112 --> 00:07:54,136
I mean, giving something away is one thing, delighting in it is something else.

79
00:07:56,298 --> 00:07:59,101
And devoted to charity.

80
00:07:59,601 --> 00:08:00,642
Devoted to charity.

81
00:08:01,264 --> 00:08:03,666
Delighting in giving and sharing.

82
00:08:03,887 --> 00:08:06,329
Delighting in giving and sharing.

83
00:08:06,348 --> 00:08:10,052
So that's one thing we, you see, parents teach children, isn't it?

84
00:08:10,074 --> 00:08:11,214
To share, you know.

85
00:08:11,814 --> 00:08:16,459
And often in children, it comes very natural to want to share, doesn't it?

86
00:08:16,480 --> 00:08:18,682
And they delight in it, you know.

87
00:08:18,702 --> 00:08:19,803
Then, of course, we get stingy.

88
00:08:21,607 --> 00:08:47,529
but that business of relinquishment so remember every time we give we have to let go of something that's the process of relinquishment of renunciation and eventually everything has to be renounced everything when we say everything has to be renounced we're talking about our relationship to something which is about holding on

89
00:08:50,311 --> 00:08:57,419
I was at a Bihari, you see, and a monk asked me, where did I get my hat?

90
00:08:59,783 --> 00:09:01,323
So I said, well, I don't know.

91
00:09:02,686 --> 00:09:05,269
He said, I'm looking for one like that, you see.

92
00:09:05,288 --> 00:09:09,433
Now, if I'd have been delighted in relinquishment, I'd have immediately given him my hat.

93
00:09:09,453 --> 00:09:10,355
But I didn't.

94
00:09:10,375 --> 00:09:11,976
I did not delight in relinquishment.

95
00:09:12,658 --> 00:09:13,919
I thought, I'm not giving him my hat.

96
00:09:16,962 --> 00:09:19,947
However, I did make up for it, because later on I sent him my hat.

97
00:09:20,416 --> 00:09:24,760
But it took about three months for me to get around to delighting in relinquishment.

98
00:09:27,604 --> 00:09:29,687
Not until I'd got another hat either.

99
00:09:30,386 --> 00:09:31,729
So you can see I've got a long way to go.

100
00:09:33,951 --> 00:09:35,913
And how is a woman accomplished in wisdom?

101
00:09:36,354 --> 00:09:42,780
So here, Visakha, a woman possesses the wisdom that's seized into the arising and passing away phenomena.

102
00:09:43,322 --> 00:09:44,263
That is noble wisdom.

103
00:09:44,513 --> 00:09:47,956
and penetrative, and leads to complete destruction of suffering.

104
00:09:48,596 --> 00:09:57,364
So that's, again, the actual spiritual path, which is about undermining certain delusions.

105
00:09:58,205 --> 00:10:03,568
And it always starts with impermanence, because that's the most obvious one you can catch.

106
00:10:03,629 --> 00:10:05,791
Anybody can see impermanence.

107
00:10:06,831 --> 00:10:09,553
If you say to somebody, you know, everything changes, they say, so what?

108
00:10:11,115 --> 00:10:14,097
I mean, the seasons change, they know it changes.

109
00:10:14,652 --> 00:10:17,615
But it's the penetrative seeing of changing.

110
00:10:18,177 --> 00:10:23,344
And remember that that penetration is not so much out in the world, it's within here.

111
00:10:23,624 --> 00:10:28,671
The sense of I is also arising and passing away and has no substance.

112
00:10:28,691 --> 00:10:31,894
When something arises and passes away, it has no real existence.

113
00:10:31,914 --> 00:10:33,758
It's not an entity, is it?

114
00:10:33,778 --> 00:10:42,870
And remember it's perceiving this constantly that allows us to come to this lovely phrase from the Buddha that there's nothing in the world worth holding on to.

115
00:10:43,576 --> 00:11:10,123
and then of course relinquishment becomes easy you stop holding on to things and that's a sign to us the more that we can do that the more we're releasing ourselves from suffering so when a woman possesses these four qualities she's heading for victory in the other world and is successful in regard to the other so

116
00:11:12,381 --> 00:11:24,359
Here the Buddha is mixing, you see, what you might call the virtues that we need for ordinary daily living and those virtues we need to liberate ourselves from suffering.

117
00:11:26,542 --> 00:11:28,024
It's quite realistic, isn't it?

118
00:11:28,044 --> 00:11:38,119
We've got to be able to handle life, we've got to be able to do things which are to our personal betterment within society, like the job we do, etc., etc.

119
00:11:39,128 --> 00:11:46,995
And that runs hand in hand with the practice, with spiritual practice, which is about liberating ourselves from suffering.

120
00:11:53,201 --> 00:12:07,397
So the four that are liberating ourselves, sorry, that are successful in this world is capable at our work, managing our lives, our domestic lives, behaving in a way that's agreeable

121
00:12:07,715 --> 00:12:18,993
to those around us, specifically our spouses and partners, and safeguarding the earnings, the wealth of our family.

122
00:12:20,154 --> 00:12:33,216
And what are those factors that bring about accomplishment, that bring success and victory in the other world?

123
00:12:36,993 --> 00:12:39,034
So that's faith, trust.

124
00:12:40,436 --> 00:12:48,142
I mean, these days, it's funny how it's translated, that is normally confidence, trust in the Buddha's teaching, you know, to put trust in it.

125
00:12:49,062 --> 00:12:49,943
Moral discipline.

126
00:12:50,244 --> 00:12:58,451
So remember that the Buddha brought our whole problem down to our ethics.

127
00:12:58,571 --> 00:13:01,052
Ethics is about relationship.

128
00:13:01,073 --> 00:13:06,357
So our relationships manifest our delusion or our wisdom.

129
00:13:07,148 --> 00:13:34,370
the way we relate to things the way we relate to ourselves that's ethics generosity which is the positive side of ethics the virtue leads to everything else and wisdom wisdom in the sense of a direct direct penetrative truth seeing which liberates us from this

130
00:13:34,739 --> 00:13:59,835
fundamental delusion about identity about who we are or what we are I can only hope my words have been of some assistance may you by developing domestic virtues as well as spiritual virtues liberate yourselves from all suffering sooner rather than later

131
00:14:01,739 --> 00:14:02,913
Sadhu.

132
00:14:03,360 --> 00:14:05,264
Sadhu.

133
00:14:05,284 --> 00:14:06,905
Sadhu.

